Note: ========================================
Note: ARM Assembly Translator Tests
Note: ========================================
Note: Comprehensive test suite for ARM assembly translation
Note: Test Coverage: Lexer, Parser, Translation, Generation, Round-trip
Note: ========================================

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/arm/arm_lexer.runa" as Lexer
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/arm/arm_parser.runa" as Parser
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/arm/arm_to_hir.runa" as ToHIR
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/backends/arm/hir_to_arm.runa" as FromHIR
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/dictionary.runa" as Dict
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout

@Reasoning:
Top-level driver for the ARM assembly translator. Runs lexer, parser,
translation, generation, and round-trip checks in that order so the
first failing test points at the lowest-level component (lexer >
parser > to-HIR > from-HIR > round-trip).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Print banner, then call each test_* proc serially. Failures are
reported inline by the assert_* helpers; this driver does not
aggregate or count results — its purpose is sequential execution
with clear stage demarcation.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- All 13 test_* procs print "[OK]" lines -> clean suite
- Any assert_* call fires "FAILED:" line -> visible in CI output
@End TestCases

Process called "run_all_arm_tests":
    proc print_string with "ARM Assembly Translator Test Suite"
    proc print_newline
    proc print_newline
    proc test_lexer_basic
    proc test_lexer_instructions
    proc test_lexer_registers
    proc test_lexer_numbers
    proc test_lexer_directives
    proc test_parser_instruction
    proc test_parser_label
    proc test_parser_directive
    proc test_parser_memory
    proc test_parser_register_list
    proc test_arm_to_hir
    proc test_hir_to_arm
    proc test_round_trip
    proc print_newline
    proc print_string with "All ARM assembly tests completed!"
    proc print_newline
End Process

@Reasoning:
Smoke test for the ARM lexer: tokenize "mov r0, r1" and assert at
least one token comes out. Intentionally minimal because more
specific assertions are in the per-category tests below.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Create string "mov r0, r1", create lexer, tokenize. Read tokens list
from lexer offset 24, assert size > 0, destroy lexer.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- Input "mov r0, r1" -> tokenize produces > 0 tokens
- Lexer state corruption -> token_count == 0 -> "FAILED: Basic
  tokenization produces tokens"
@End TestCases

Process called "test_lexer_basic":
    proc print_string with "Testing ARM lexer (basic)..."
    proc print_newline

    Let source be proc create_string_literal with "mov r0, r1"
    Let lexer be proc create_lexer from Lexer with source
    proc tokenize from Lexer with lexer

    Let tokens be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let token_count be proc size from List with tokens
    Let token_check_basic be token_count is greater than 0
    proc assert_true with token_check_basic, "Basic tokenization produces tokens"

    proc destroy_lexer from Lexer with lexer
    proc print_string with "  ✓ Basic lexer tests passed"
    proc print_newline
End Process

@Reasoning:
Verifies the lexer recognizes seven common ARM mnemonics as
INSTRUCTION-class tokens. Catches a regression where an alias table
update missed a core instruction (e.g. push/pop dropped after a
keyword-set refactor).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Tokenize "mov add sub ldr str push pop". Assert token count == 7.
Loop i in 0..7, read token at offset 0 (type tag), assert each
equals 1 (INSTRUCTION).
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- All 7 mnemonics classify as INSTRUCTION (type 1), passed
- Any mnemonic classified differently -> "Token is INSTRUCTION" fails
- Lexer merges two tokens -> count != 7 -> "Instruction tokenization" fails
@End TestCases

Process called "test_lexer_instructions":
    proc print_string with "Testing ARM lexer (instructions)..."
    proc print_newline

    Let source be proc create_string_literal with "mov add sub ldr str push pop"
    Let lexer be proc create_lexer from Lexer with source
    proc tokenize from Lexer with lexer

    Let tokens be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let token_count be proc size from List with tokens

    Note: Should have 7 instruction tokens
    proc assert_equals with token_count, 7, "Instruction tokenization"

    Note: Verify all are instruction tokens
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than 7:
        Let token be proc get from List with tokens, i
        Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0
        proc assert_equals with token_type, 1, "Token is INSTRUCTION"
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc destroy_lexer from Lexer with lexer
    proc print_string with "  ✓ Instruction lexer tests passed"
    proc print_newline
End Process

@Reasoning:
Verifies register tokenization for both numbered (r0, r1) and
named (sp, lr, pc) ARM registers. The lexer must classify all five
as REGISTER tokens (type 2) so the parser can treat them
uniformly in operand position.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Tokenize "r0 r1 sp lr pc". Assert count == 5. Loop and assert each
token type == 2 (REGISTER).
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- All 5 names classify as REGISTER (type 2), passed
- Lexer treats "sp" as instruction or identifier -> "Token is REGISTER" fails
- Count != 5 -> "Register tokenization" fails
@End TestCases

Process called "test_lexer_registers":
    proc print_string with "Testing ARM lexer (registers)..."
    proc print_newline

    Let source be proc create_string_literal with "r0 r1 sp lr pc"
    Let lexer be proc create_lexer from Lexer with source
    proc tokenize from Lexer with lexer

    Let tokens be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let token_count be proc size from List with tokens

    Note: Should have 5 register tokens
    proc assert_equals with token_count, 5, "Register tokenization"

    Note: Verify all are register tokens
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than 5:
        Let token be proc get from List with tokens, i
        Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0
        proc assert_equals with token_type, 2, "Token is REGISTER"
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc destroy_lexer from Lexer with lexer
    proc print_string with "  ✓ Register lexer tests passed"
    proc print_newline
End Process

@Reasoning:
Verifies numeric literal forms: ARM immediates prefixed with "#",
hex (#0xFF), negative (#-17), and bare decimal (16). The lexer must
accept all four notations.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Tokenize "#42 #0xFF #-17 16". Assert count > 0. The test does not
fix an exact count because the lexer may produce separate # tokens
or fused immediate tokens, both of which are valid.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- Input "#42 #0xFF #-17 16" -> > 0 tokens produced
- Lexer rejects hex/negative -> count == 0 -> "Number tokenization" fails
@End TestCases

Process called "test_lexer_numbers":
    proc print_string with "Testing ARM lexer (numbers)..."
    proc print_newline

    Let source be proc create_string_literal with "#42 #0xFF #-17 16"
    Let lexer be proc create_lexer from Lexer with source
    proc tokenize from Lexer with lexer

    Let tokens be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let token_count be proc size from List with tokens

    Note: Should have tokens for each number (with # prefix tokens)
    Let token_check_number be token_count is greater than 0
    proc assert_true with token_check_number, "Number tokenization"

    proc destroy_lexer from Lexer with lexer
    proc print_string with "  ✓ Number lexer tests passed"
    proc print_newline
End Process

@Reasoning:
Verifies GNU-as directive tokenization: .text, .data, .globl,
.section. Directives have type 3 to distinguish them from
instructions and labels.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Tokenize ".text .data .globl .section". Assert count == 4. Loop and
assert each token type == 3 (DIRECTIVE).
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- All 4 directives classify as DIRECTIVE (type 3), passed
- Lexer drops the dot -> may still tokenize but classifies as INSTRUCTION
  -> "Token is DIRECTIVE" fails
- Count != 4 -> "Directive tokenization" fails
@End TestCases

Process called "test_lexer_directives":
    proc print_string with "Testing ARM lexer (directives)..."
    proc print_newline

    Let source be proc create_string_literal with ".text .data .globl .section"
    Let lexer be proc create_lexer from Lexer with source
    proc tokenize from Lexer with lexer

    Let tokens be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let token_count be proc size from List with tokens

    Note: Should have 4 directive tokens
    proc assert_equals with token_count, 4, "Directive tokenization"

    Note: Verify all are directive tokens
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than 4:
        Let token be proc get from List with tokens, i
        Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0
        proc assert_equals with token_type, 3, "Token is DIRECTIVE"
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc destroy_lexer from Lexer with lexer
    proc print_string with "  ✓ Directive lexer tests passed"
    proc print_newline
End Process

@Reasoning:
Verifies the parser builds an AST node for a complete instruction
with two operands (register destination + immediate source). The
"has children" assertion catches a regression where the parser
produces a bare instruction node with no operands attached.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Tokenize "mov r0, #42", parse. Assert ast is not null. Read children
list from ast offset 24; assert size > 0.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- Input "mov r0, #42" -> AST with two operands as children, passed
- Parser returns null on valid form -> "Instruction parsed" fails
- Parser builds AST but drops operands -> "Instruction has operands" fails
@End TestCases

Process called "test_parser_instruction":
    proc print_string with "Testing ARM parser (instruction)..."
    proc print_newline

    Let source be proc create_string_literal with "mov r0, #42"
    Let lexer be proc create_lexer from Lexer with source
    proc tokenize from Lexer with lexer

    Let parser be proc create_parser from Parser with lexer
    Let ast be proc parse from Parser with parser

    proc assert_not_null with ast, "Instruction parsed"

    Note: Verify AST has children
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 24
    Let child_count be proc size from List with children
    Let child_check be child_count is greater than 0
    proc assert_true with child_check, "Instruction has operands"

    proc destroy_arm_node from Parser with ast
    proc destroy_parser from Parser with parser
    proc destroy_lexer from Lexer with lexer
    proc print_string with "  ✓ Instruction parser tests passed"
    proc print_newline
End Process

@Reasoning:
Verifies the parser handles a bare label ("main:"). Catches a
regression where the parser requires an instruction or directive
after the colon and rejects label-only lines.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Tokenize "main:", parse. Assert ast is not null.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- Input "main:" -> non-null label AST node, passed
- Parser rejects bare label -> ast == 0 -> "Label parsed" fails
@End TestCases

